WEBVTT

00:00.027 --> 00:03.735
<i>♪ You'll be back, soon you'll see ♪</i>

00:03.770 --> 00:07.416
<i>♪ You'll remember you belong to me ♪</i>

00:07.450 --> 00:11.431
<i>♪ And when push comes to shove ♪</i>

00:11.472 --> 00:14.807
♪ I will send the fully armed
battalion... ♪

00:14.842 --> 00:17.510
Oh, I see how it is.

00:17.544 --> 00:19.178
Yeah, it's called strategy.

00:19.213 --> 00:20.580
Yeah, where I'm from
it's called cheating.

00:20.614 --> 00:21.848
[COUGHING]

00:21.882 --> 00:24.250
Uh, you all right, Willow?

00:24.284 --> 00:27.353
I swear, if they wrote
a Broadway musical about me

00:27.388 --> 00:30.256
it would be called "The Sound of Mucus."

00:30.290 --> 00:31.691
[LAUGHTER]

00:31.725 --> 00:33.593
Mine would be called, "Mama Mastectomy."

00:33.627 --> 00:35.128
- Ooh.
- More like,

00:35.162 --> 00:36.629
"Thoroughly Mortal Millie."

00:36.664 --> 00:38.765
- [LAUGHTER]
- That's a good one.

00:38.799 --> 00:41.367
"The Phantom of the Operation."

00:41.402 --> 00:43.369
[LAUGHTER]

00:43.404 --> 00:45.772
Willow, how long have you had that cough?

00:45.806 --> 00:48.808
Mine'd be, "Liver Let Die."

00:48.842 --> 00:50.276
Liver-less.

00:50.310 --> 00:51.644
Of course, that's a Bond film,

00:51.679 --> 00:53.279
not a Broadway musical,

00:53.313 --> 00:55.148
but unlike you, I'm cool with cheating.

00:55.182 --> 00:56.616
- She's right.
- Well, actually,

00:56.650 --> 00:58.451
I was thinking of the Guns N' Roses song.

00:58.485 --> 00:59.819
[LAUGHING]

00:59.853 --> 01:03.556
So, Max, what's your cancer musical?

01:03.590 --> 01:06.559
♪ Forever and ever

01:06.593 --> 01:08.795
What's the matter, Max? No jokes today?

01:08.829 --> 01:10.296
Where's your sense of tumor?

01:10.330 --> 01:14.467
[LAUGHTER]

01:14.501 --> 01:19.539
Synced & corrected by -robtor-
www.addic7ed.com

01:19.573 --> 01:22.341
[SOBBING]

01:26.346 --> 01:30.249
Thank you, Andre. That was so brave.

01:30.284 --> 01:32.185
Nice connecting.

01:35.923 --> 01:39.492
Lauren, how about you?

01:39.526 --> 01:41.894
I know that you're still
getting acclimated

01:41.929 --> 01:43.863
but we would love to hear from you.

01:45.933 --> 01:48.467
Your friend just visited?

01:49.303 --> 01:51.971
Maybe you want to talk about
how that made you feel?

01:52.806 --> 01:54.540
No.

01:54.575 --> 01:56.776
But, um, thank you.

01:56.810 --> 01:58.778
<i>[SOMBER MUSIC]</i>

01:58.812 --> 02:00.747
Maybe at evening group.

02:00.781 --> 02:02.682
<i>♪ </i>

02:02.716 --> 02:05.384
Have a beautiful morning, everyone.

02:05.419 --> 02:07.353
- Thanks for sharing, Andre.
- Good session.

02:07.387 --> 02:08.788
Way to go.

02:09.288 --> 02:11.190
Yeah, hi. Come in. It's Martin.

02:11.225 --> 02:12.859
No, babe, I hear what you're
saying loud and clear

02:12.893 --> 02:14.694
but she needs to try new
things, all right?

02:14.728 --> 02:16.462
And plus, literally, there's
nothing cooler

02:16.497 --> 02:17.563
that a kid could do.

02:19.266 --> 02:21.467
Yes, or an adult. You got me, okay?

02:21.502 --> 02:23.703
But she is going.

02:23.737 --> 02:26.339
Yes, I'll call you later. Love you.

02:27.274 --> 02:29.375
Husbands, am I right?

02:29.409 --> 02:31.310
Anyway, sorry about the mess.
Me and Sameera are going

02:31.345 --> 02:33.946
for a sleep over at the
Museum of Natural History later

02:33.981 --> 02:35.281
and I am so excited.

02:35.315 --> 02:37.583
I visited Lauren in rehab.

02:39.419 --> 02:40.936
Okay.

02:41.255 --> 02:42.588
Well, that happened.

02:42.623 --> 02:43.956
I shouldn't have done that.

02:43.991 --> 02:45.315
Yeah.

02:47.461 --> 02:49.695
- How was she?
- [GRUNTS]

02:50.364 --> 02:51.397
I don't know. She wouldn't even

02:51.431 --> 02:53.365
look at me, man, just...

02:53.801 --> 02:55.468
and then she just told me to leave.

02:55.502 --> 02:57.270
Well, you invaded her privacy.

02:57.304 --> 02:58.571
Yeah, but, come on. I'm her friend.

02:58.605 --> 02:59.906
Yeah, but you may remind her

02:59.940 --> 03:01.440
of an environment that's toxic.

03:01.475 --> 03:03.409
- You understand?
- Toxic?

03:03.443 --> 03:04.777
The hospital. This... this place.

03:04.812 --> 03:06.050
All the stress that it caused her.

03:06.084 --> 03:07.313
Oh, yeah.

03:07.347 --> 03:10.449
Besides, the first few days
in rehab are a huge transition.

03:10.484 --> 03:11.617
- You shouldn't have...
- I thought you were

03:11.652 --> 03:12.752
supposed to be a good listener.

03:12.786 --> 03:14.587
Do... ugh.

03:14.621 --> 03:17.523
You know what, if you want me
to stand here and make you

03:17.558 --> 03:19.258
feel better about doing something that I

03:19.293 --> 03:22.428
strongly advised you not to,
I'm not going to.

03:22.462 --> 03:23.696
Because the person
that I'm concerned about

03:23.730 --> 03:25.765
right now is Lauren. Not you.

03:25.799 --> 03:28.868
[PHONE BUZZING]

03:28.902 --> 03:30.870
What? Really?

03:30.904 --> 03:34.273
The old saved-by-the-page?
Huh? That old chestnut?

03:34.308 --> 03:36.709
Ten year old boy status post
heart transplant

03:36.743 --> 03:38.044
now with respiratory arrest

03:38.078 --> 03:39.812
during the Pope's procession down 5th.

03:39.847 --> 03:40.813
Trauma one.

03:40.848 --> 03:43.516
126, 150/92, and 22.

03:43.550 --> 03:46.819
0-2 sat 92 on 100% non rebreather.

03:46.854 --> 03:48.621
Jimmy, your parents are right
behind you, okay?

03:48.655 --> 03:49.956
- And I'm here.
- Oh, good. Jump in.

03:49.990 --> 03:51.557
Jimmy, we're right here.

03:51.592 --> 03:53.626
Ten years old. Recent heart transplant.

03:53.660 --> 03:54.961
0-2 sats still in low 90s.

03:54.995 --> 03:56.629
Push another 10 milligrams of Lasix.

03:56.663 --> 04:00.066
Jimmy, everything's gonna be okay.
Just keep breathing, okay?

04:00.100 --> 04:01.701
His lungs are filled with fluid.

04:01.735 --> 04:03.703
Heart failure?

04:03.737 --> 04:06.038
Most likely secondary acute rejection,

04:06.073 --> 04:08.541
which we need a left
ventricular biopsy to confirm.

04:08.575 --> 04:10.843
Why is he rejecting the transplant?

04:10.878 --> 04:13.346
<i>[DRAMATIC MUSIC]</i>

04:13.380 --> 04:14.747
God only knows.

04:14.781 --> 04:16.882
<i>♪ </i>

04:16.916 --> 04:20.553
<i>[RHYTHMIC MUSIC]</i>

04:20.587 --> 04:22.388
Good morning, Mr. Brandt.

04:22.422 --> 04:24.023
Oh, okay.

04:24.057 --> 04:27.360
<i>♪ </i>

04:27.394 --> 04:30.062
Uh... [FAKES COUGH]

04:30.097 --> 04:32.339
Oh, sorry.

04:32.900 --> 04:35.501
You know how young women are sex positive

04:35.535 --> 04:37.136
and everything nowadays.

04:38.538 --> 04:40.773
[CHUCKLING] Yes.

04:40.807 --> 04:43.676
I understand you're under
a protocol at Baptist?

04:43.710 --> 04:46.712
- Yeah, for colon cancer.
- Stage 3.

04:46.747 --> 04:49.715
Worst 18 months of my life.

04:49.750 --> 04:52.952
Of course, until I met
this gorgeous woman.

04:52.986 --> 04:54.921
[CHUCKLES]

04:54.955 --> 04:57.790
So what would you like me to do for you?

04:57.824 --> 05:00.059
Well, it's pretty simple.

05:01.495 --> 05:03.930
I want this thing removed.

05:03.964 --> 05:06.465
Well, that thing is how they administer

05:06.500 --> 05:08.701
your chemotherapy
drugs for your colon cancer.

05:08.735 --> 05:10.903
I'm not interested in that either.

05:10.938 --> 05:13.072
He wants to stop the chemo.

05:13.974 --> 05:15.808
Have you discussed that
with your oncologist

05:15.842 --> 05:17.710
- over at Baptist because...
- Look, look.

05:17.744 --> 05:19.545
Can you take the catheter out or not?

05:19.579 --> 05:21.547
But the treatment
is prolonging your life.

05:21.581 --> 05:24.550
It... it might be,

05:24.584 --> 05:28.087
but I'm certain as hell not living.

05:28.121 --> 05:32.732
Tethered to a hospital,
dragged down by drugs.

05:33.460 --> 05:36.095
I'd rather spend some time traveling

05:36.129 --> 05:38.431
with this young woman.

05:38.465 --> 05:40.633
Well, all my patients would
rather be doing something

05:40.667 --> 05:42.935
besides chemotherapy, but it's vital

05:42.970 --> 05:45.104
in order to treat the disease.

05:45.138 --> 05:47.440
Haven't you ever been in love?

05:47.474 --> 05:50.076
<i>[SENTIMENTAL MUSIC]</i>

05:50.110 --> 05:52.912
What wouldn't you give for just a little

05:52.946 --> 05:54.580
bit more of it?

05:54.614 --> 05:59.752
<i>♪ </i>

05:59.786 --> 06:02.588
Meeting with Brennan from HCC at 9:00.

06:02.622 --> 06:04.090
Uh, maintenance review panel at 10:00,

06:04.124 --> 06:06.525
Morbidity and Mortality
conference at 11:00.

06:06.560 --> 06:08.494
I have a sense of humor, right?

06:08.528 --> 06:10.629
I don't find you funny
but that's mainly because

06:10.664 --> 06:11.797
most of your decisions ruin my life.

06:11.832 --> 06:13.099
Ah.

06:13.133 --> 06:15.101
You owe a call to the head of the board

06:15.135 --> 06:16.635
about year-end budgets,
and you're meeting Georgia

06:16.670 --> 06:17.937
for birthing class at 1:30.

06:17.971 --> 06:20.106
- Can you push it?
- Yeah, okay.

06:20.140 --> 06:22.108
- That was funny.
- What? No, it wasn't a joke.

06:22.142 --> 06:25.011
I just... I'm not really in
the push-push mood today.

06:25.045 --> 06:27.813
Hmm. Yeah, because birthing
class is all about your mood.

06:27.848 --> 06:29.482
It's the... you know, I don't know.

06:29.516 --> 06:31.617
It's like, something about
joking about death

06:31.651 --> 06:34.787
that's just not to me very funny.

06:34.821 --> 06:36.622
You know, as much as I'd love
to keep talking to you

06:36.656 --> 06:38.624
about your sense of humor

06:38.658 --> 06:41.527
do you remember speaking to the
Secret Service a few weeks ago?

06:41.561 --> 06:43.796
Maybe, but if I told ya
I'd have to kill ya.

06:43.830 --> 06:44.897
Don't give up your day job.

06:44.931 --> 06:46.132
Come on, that was funny.

06:46.166 --> 06:47.800
- They're in your office.
- Ugh.

06:47.834 --> 06:49.802
<i>[DRUMMING]</i>

06:52.506 --> 06:55.975
Hm. Uh, Max Goodwin, Medical Director.

06:56.009 --> 06:57.243
Welcome to New Amsterdam.

06:57.277 --> 06:59.678
Thank you. I am Cardinal Mancini.

06:59.713 --> 07:00.980
- Hi.
- This is agent Hayes

07:01.014 --> 07:02.681
and agent Larson...

07:02.716 --> 07:04.250
- How you doing?
- From the Secret Service.

07:04.284 --> 07:05.584
Cool.

07:05.619 --> 07:07.019
You know why we're here?

07:07.054 --> 07:10.523
Uh, ye... uh, yeah, no.

07:10.557 --> 07:13.259
The Pope is addressing
the UN this afternoon.

07:13.293 --> 07:16.662
Right, the Pope
is addressing the... right.

07:16.696 --> 07:18.164
- Yeah, I remember.
- Ah, yes.

07:18.198 --> 07:20.232
And as Papal Security Liaison,

07:20.267 --> 07:22.168
it falls to me to secure

07:22.202 --> 07:25.004
your presidential bay
in case of an emergency,

07:25.038 --> 07:26.272
God forbid.

07:26.306 --> 07:28.841
Sure. Uh, great. Well, I'm happy to help.

07:28.875 --> 07:30.843
You need the presidential bay?

07:30.877 --> 07:32.211
- Yes, sir.
- And surrounding floors.

07:32.245 --> 07:34.646
Ah, yes. And the surrounding floors.

07:35.115 --> 07:38.184
Well, I don't love the sound
of surrounding floors.

07:38.218 --> 07:40.186
This is a working hospital.

07:40.220 --> 07:43.022
- It's a precaution.
- And merely formality.

07:44.257 --> 07:46.992
You'll hardly tell we're here.

07:48.662 --> 07:50.696
<i>[TENSE MUSIC]</i>

07:50.730 --> 07:53.032
- Please make room.
- Excuse us.

07:53.066 --> 07:55.201
Let's go, let's go. Keep it moving.

07:55.235 --> 07:56.869
[OVERLAPPING CHATTER]

07:56.903 --> 07:58.637
All the way to the end
of the hall, please.

07:58.672 --> 08:01.740
- Behind you.
- Let's go, let's go.

08:01.775 --> 08:04.210
Keep moving, please.

08:04.244 --> 08:07.580
Hate to say this, but I can
kinda tell you're here.

08:07.614 --> 08:08.781
<i>♪ </i>

08:08.815 --> 08:10.149
Let's see.

08:10.183 --> 08:13.119
[INDISTINCT MURMURING]

08:13.153 --> 08:14.887
I'm not seeing any significant scarring.

08:14.921 --> 08:16.889
It would be a very mild surgery.

08:16.923 --> 08:18.757
- Let her rip.
- [CHUCKLES]

08:18.792 --> 08:20.926
Before we let her rip I need to make sure

08:20.961 --> 08:22.628
that you're absolutely certain

08:22.662 --> 08:23.896
that you wanna end your chemotherapy.

08:23.930 --> 08:26.132
Never more sure of anything.

08:27.367 --> 08:29.335
Okay. Well, while we wait

08:29.369 --> 08:31.003
for your records to be sent over

08:31.037 --> 08:32.938
from Baptist, we can schedule
the procedure,

08:32.972 --> 08:34.573
and then we'll take it from...

08:34.607 --> 08:35.908
- Dr. Sharpe.
- Lila, I'm with a patient.

08:35.942 --> 08:37.176
I'm sorry, I tried to tell them.

08:37.210 --> 08:38.977
- Tell who?
- Yeah, she's the one.

08:39.011 --> 08:40.846
Ma'am, I'm gonna have
to ask you a few questions.

08:40.881 --> 08:42.914
- I haven't done anything.
- Don't you touch her! Sheila!

08:42.948 --> 08:44.350
- Come on, let's go.
- Sorry, excuse me.

08:44.384 --> 08:46.652
- What's going on, please?
- Hi, I'm Carl Jimenez.

08:46.686 --> 08:48.787
I'm Mr. Brandt's legal guardian.

08:48.822 --> 08:50.990
That woman kidnapped him.

08:51.024 --> 08:53.993
<i>[OMINOUS MUSIC]</i>

08:54.027 --> 08:55.995
<i>♪ </i>

08:56.029 --> 08:57.296
Gentlemen?

08:57.330 --> 08:59.131
We have received a credible death threat

08:59.166 --> 09:01.333
against the Pope
from within this hospital.

09:01.368 --> 09:03.102
Security will need to be heightened.

09:03.136 --> 09:06.805
Uh, sorry. Wait, who here
would threaten the Pope?

09:06.840 --> 09:08.907
As it turns out, one of your doctors.

09:09.809 --> 09:11.310
Dr. Vijay Kapoor.

09:11.344 --> 09:14.313
<i>[TENSE MUSIC]</i>

09:14.347 --> 09:15.748
<i>♪ </i>

09:18.429 --> 09:20.763
<i>It's not as simple as whether I did</i>

09:20.798 --> 09:22.465
<i>or did not try</i>
<i>to kill the Pope.</i>

09:22.499 --> 09:24.200
How could it possibly not be that simple?

09:24.234 --> 09:25.976
Dr. Kapoor coated the bed

09:26.001 --> 09:27.635
in the presidential bay
with a known poison.

09:27.660 --> 09:28.793
Sorry, poison?

09:28.828 --> 09:30.228
It was oleander petals!

09:30.263 --> 09:32.197
- Which are poisonous.
- But it was a gift.

09:32.231 --> 09:34.833
It represents heart chakra.
The Pope has a big heart.

09:34.867 --> 09:36.635
Yeah, Vijay, couldn't you just

09:36.669 --> 09:37.969
have given the Pope a normal gift?

09:38.004 --> 09:40.539
I would have, but what
do you give someone

09:40.573 --> 09:42.073
who lives in the Vatican?

09:42.108 --> 09:43.808
Pope is a man of peace.

09:43.843 --> 09:46.711
He supports women's rights
and gay people.

09:46.746 --> 09:49.648
And I heard a rumor that he
sneaks out of the Vatican

09:49.682 --> 09:52.751
disguised to help to feed
the poor people.

09:52.785 --> 09:56.087
As you can see, Dr. Kapoor
made an innocent mistake.

09:56.122 --> 09:57.656
[LAUGHS] He loves the Pope.

09:57.690 --> 09:59.925
- I love the Pope.
- Loves him.

09:59.959 --> 10:01.226
[PHONE CHIMING]

10:01.260 --> 10:04.863
<i>♪ </i>

10:04.897 --> 10:06.731
Your background check came back clear.

10:06.766 --> 10:09.768
So he can go, right?

10:09.802 --> 10:11.770
<i>♪ </i>

10:11.804 --> 10:14.172
- I'll check.
- Great, thank you.

10:14.207 --> 10:16.508
I mean, if I actually wanted
to kill the Pope

10:16.542 --> 10:18.677
I would have used white snakeroot petals.

10:18.711 --> 10:19.878
- Mm-hmm.
- Excuse me?

10:19.912 --> 10:21.913
Yeah, it's faster and untraceable.

10:21.948 --> 10:23.615
That's exactly what killed

10:23.649 --> 10:25.917
Abraham Lincoln's mother, you know.

10:25.952 --> 10:27.786
Take a seat, please, Dr. Kapoor.

10:27.820 --> 10:29.087
What?

10:29.121 --> 10:30.738
You're on your own, pal.

10:31.612 --> 10:33.180
Please take a seat.

10:39.620 --> 10:42.789
So, uh, Jimmy's heart biopsy results

10:42.824 --> 10:44.624
show signs of acute rejection

10:44.659 --> 10:46.159
and that's why your son collapsed.

10:46.194 --> 10:47.828
Well, is he gonna be all right?

10:47.862 --> 10:49.896
Well, I've increased
his immunosuppressants

10:49.931 --> 10:52.666
and that should treat this
episode but we need to find out

10:52.700 --> 10:54.101
why it happened in the first place.

10:54.135 --> 10:55.836
Now were there any changes in his diet?

10:55.870 --> 10:58.975
Any rashes, colds, or upset stomach?

11:00.143 --> 11:01.608
Hm.

11:01.642 --> 11:03.610
Well, can you think
of anything different?

11:03.644 --> 11:05.912
Like, anything out of the ordinary?

11:12.854 --> 11:14.282
Mrs. Corrigan?

11:14.317 --> 11:16.590
<i>[TENSE MUSIC]</i>

11:16.624 --> 11:19.126
Our insurance paid for the transplant,

11:19.160 --> 11:22.429
but they didn't pay for any
of the post op medications.

11:22.463 --> 11:23.597
<i>♪ </i>

11:23.631 --> 11:25.599
Doesn't make any sense.

11:25.633 --> 11:29.169
The pills, they cost over $9,000 a month.

11:29.203 --> 11:31.605
<i>♪ </i>

11:31.639 --> 11:35.108
Our church held a fundraiser,
but it wasn't enough.

11:35.143 --> 11:36.643
Okay. And?

11:36.677 --> 11:38.178
<i>♪ </i>

11:38.212 --> 11:40.213
We, uh, started

11:40.248 --> 11:42.816
spreading out the pills.

11:42.850 --> 11:44.451
Like,

11:44.485 --> 11:47.487
just giving him one every other day.

11:47.522 --> 11:49.456
We were trying to make them last.

11:49.490 --> 11:51.158
<i>♪ </i>

11:51.192 --> 11:55.495
Um... that's what made Jimmy sick.

11:55.530 --> 11:56.630
We did this.

11:56.664 --> 11:58.287
Well, I mean...

11:58.322 --> 12:00.700
it's real easy to blame yourselves.

12:00.735 --> 12:02.869
That's not going to make Jimmy
better, okay?

12:02.904 --> 12:04.804
We just need to make sure
that it never happens again.

12:04.839 --> 12:05.839
All right?

12:05.873 --> 12:08.008
But it will.

12:08.042 --> 12:09.843
We can't afford the pills.

12:09.877 --> 12:11.011
[SNIFFLES]

12:11.045 --> 12:12.979
What are we supposed to do?

12:13.014 --> 12:16.783
<i>♪ </i>

12:18.786 --> 12:21.521
I'm just doing my job.
Walter's living will

12:21.556 --> 12:23.156
specifically states any and all known

12:23.191 --> 12:24.858
medical treatments should be explored.

12:24.892 --> 12:27.494
Okay. But Sheila?

12:27.528 --> 12:30.030
You can't honestly think that
that sweet lady's a kidnapper.

12:30.064 --> 12:31.831
She removed him from his residence

12:31.866 --> 12:34.034
- and ran away with him.
- They're in love.

12:34.068 --> 12:36.503
Look, I'm just trying to protect Walter

12:36.537 --> 12:38.238
from the story I see all the time.

12:38.272 --> 12:40.173
An older man, alone, vulnerable,

12:40.208 --> 12:42.483
- meets a younger woman...
- She's 75.

12:42.518 --> 12:46.179
25 or 75, she wants him
to stop his cancer treatment.

12:46.214 --> 12:48.114
Now, I've been granted
his healthcare decisions

12:48.149 --> 12:51.017
because frankly, his healthcare
proxy was asleep at the wheel.

12:51.052 --> 12:54.221
So here I am doing the best I can.

12:56.891 --> 12:58.692
I can appreciate that.

12:58.726 --> 13:01.094
So, tell me.

13:01.128 --> 13:03.697
Is stopping treatment
in Walter's best interest?

13:03.731 --> 13:05.765
Medically, no.

13:05.800 --> 13:07.867
But I have to respect
the patient's wishes.

13:07.902 --> 13:11.238
Well, legally,
you have to respect my wishes.

13:11.272 --> 13:13.807
And even though Walt's a pain in the ass,

13:13.841 --> 13:16.042
I'm just trying to keep him alive.

13:17.578 --> 13:18.979
<i>He's trying to kill me.</i>

13:19.013 --> 13:21.214
If it were left up to Carl

13:21.249 --> 13:24.951
I would be alone,
rotting in my apartment,

13:24.986 --> 13:27.557
having the life drained out of me.

13:28.256 --> 13:30.901
[SIGHS] He's doing
what he thinks is best.

13:30.901 --> 13:33.369
He thinks Sheila pushed me.

13:33.403 --> 13:35.404
The whole thing was my idea.

13:35.438 --> 13:37.973
Unfortunately the law
may not see it that way.

13:38.008 --> 13:41.610
I don't have a lot of time
left on this Earth.

13:41.645 --> 13:45.281
And the law won't let me live
the way I want to.

13:46.809 --> 13:48.217
That ain't right.

13:48.251 --> 13:51.220
<i>[SOMBER MUSIC]</i>

13:51.254 --> 13:54.723
<i>♪ </i>

13:54.758 --> 13:57.226
Maybe there is something that we can do.

13:57.653 --> 13:59.895
Get the law on our side.

13:59.930 --> 14:02.231
<i>[HOPEFUL MUSIC]</i>

14:02.265 --> 14:04.266
- Yo, Max!
- How can I help?

14:04.301 --> 14:05.935
Change the fundamental idiocracy

14:05.969 --> 14:07.770
- of American healthcare?
- I'm working on it.

14:07.804 --> 14:10.339
I've got this kid,
just had a heart transplant,

14:10.373 --> 14:11.907
family can't afford the post op meds.

14:11.942 --> 14:13.509
What's their financial profile?

14:13.543 --> 14:15.045
Married, stable.

14:15.079 --> 14:17.913
Dad's a security guard who
pulls in about 45K a year.

14:17.948 --> 14:19.415
Too much to qualify for Medicaid.

14:19.449 --> 14:20.683
Or the Community Care Fund.

14:20.717 --> 14:22.518
Well, we can help them in the short term

14:22.552 --> 14:24.253
but they need a long term solution.

14:24.287 --> 14:27.756
[SIGHS] Working class,
just caught in the middle.

14:27.791 --> 14:29.692
<i>[SOMBER MUSIC]</i>

14:29.726 --> 14:31.360
Maybe not.

14:31.394 --> 14:34.763
<i>[HOPEFUL MUSIC]</i>

14:34.798 --> 14:35.798
Um...

14:37.400 --> 14:38.968
You could get a divorce.

14:40.637 --> 14:43.005
Is this a joke?

14:43.039 --> 14:46.442
Look, if Patricia is a single
mom with no income,

14:46.476 --> 14:48.444
she and Jimmy could qualify for Medicaid.

14:48.478 --> 14:50.713
And Medicaid would cover
the cost of Jimmy's medication.

14:50.747 --> 14:53.793
But we love each other.

14:54.384 --> 14:56.318
Well, no one's questioning that.

14:56.353 --> 14:59.455
And as Catholics we don't
even believe in divorce.

14:59.489 --> 15:02.122
You can't ask us to break
something that's unbreakable.

15:02.156 --> 15:04.326
- I... I can't even...
- I'm sorry.

15:04.361 --> 15:08.464
It's just, uh, the system is flawed.

15:08.498 --> 15:12.501
And so is the solution, but
I can't think of a better one.

15:15.898 --> 15:18.609
Get divorced, save your son.

15:22.379 --> 15:25.547
[MACHINE FLATLINING]

15:25.582 --> 15:26.815
What happened?

15:26.850 --> 15:28.684
I don't know, I just got the page.

15:28.718 --> 15:30.138
Heart rate 140. BP 90 over palp.

15:30.173 --> 15:32.330
- Respiratory rate 22.
- She collapsed at work.

15:32.365 --> 15:34.456
EMS just dropped off.
Any history of infection?

15:34.491 --> 15:35.524
No, none.

15:35.558 --> 15:37.860
She's tachy, hypotensive,
warm to the touch.

15:37.894 --> 15:39.495
- Sepsis?
- She has a hot, red,

15:39.529 --> 15:40.896
macular rash around her j-tube.

15:40.930 --> 15:42.998
BOTH: Cellulitis.
- Looks like it.

15:43.033 --> 15:44.666
That's preventable.
Helen, your people let her

15:44.701 --> 15:46.535
walk out with an infection? Who's next?

15:46.569 --> 15:48.704
Max, I paged you here as
her friend, not as her doctor.

15:48.738 --> 15:50.439
Let's get her to Trauma One!

15:50.473 --> 15:51.940
I've got this under control.

15:51.975 --> 15:53.042
Do you?

15:53.076 --> 15:55.510
<i>[TENSE MUSIC]</i>

15:55.544 --> 15:58.013
I'm gonna give you a minute to
think about what you just said.

15:58.048 --> 16:02.051
<i>♪ </i>

16:08.359 --> 16:09.778
<i>- Max.
- Hm?</i>

16:09.812 --> 16:11.427
<i>- Birthing class?
- I'll be there.</i>

16:11.462 --> 16:12.528
Okay.

16:15.365 --> 16:16.699
How is she?

16:16.733 --> 16:18.701
She's stable, but not out of the woods.

16:18.735 --> 16:20.203
Yeah. She was coughing
this morning but there was

16:20.237 --> 16:21.671
- no indication...
- Setbacks happen.

16:21.705 --> 16:23.573
You're calling sepsis a setback?

16:23.607 --> 16:25.241
Is this your way of apologizing?

16:25.275 --> 16:27.610
She was laughing at her symptoms.

16:27.644 --> 16:30.379
This morning in chemo.
Everyone was laughing,

16:30.414 --> 16:32.281
and I couldn't done something.

16:32.316 --> 16:34.784
I could've gotten someone.

16:34.809 --> 16:37.386
She was laughing at her symptoms.

16:37.421 --> 16:41.691
She was laughing
because of her symptoms, Max.

16:41.725 --> 16:43.759
<i>[SOMBER MUSIC]</i>

16:43.794 --> 16:45.261
There's a difference.

16:45.295 --> 16:49.599
<i>♪ </i>

16:49.633 --> 16:52.703
One, two, three, four, five.

16:53.974 --> 16:55.204
No.

16:56.473 --> 16:58.541
Five, four, three, two, one?

16:59.610 --> 17:01.210
No.

17:01.245 --> 17:04.780
Can you think of any other
five digit password?

17:04.815 --> 17:07.916
As soon as I scan your email
you're free to go.

17:07.951 --> 17:11.253
I want to help you
but I rarely use email.

17:11.288 --> 17:14.457
Honestly, I thought
it was a passing trend.

17:14.491 --> 17:16.125
What do you use?

17:16.160 --> 17:18.728
A cup of tea and a conversation.

17:18.762 --> 17:20.496
[EXASPERATED SIGH]

17:20.531 --> 17:23.833
Is... is it your back
that's bothering you?

17:23.867 --> 17:25.568
Maybe I can help.

17:25.602 --> 17:27.303
You wanna help?

17:27.337 --> 17:29.438
Remember your password.

17:29.473 --> 17:31.407
Hello, John Wilkes Booth. [LAUGHING]

17:31.441 --> 17:32.808
I warned you not to do it, didn't I?

17:32.843 --> 17:35.278
- Ha.
- You did?

17:35.312 --> 17:37.313
Yeah. Hell yeah, I did,
because it was idiotic.

17:37.347 --> 17:38.748
You mean you knew about this little stunt

17:38.782 --> 17:40.416
and you decided not to report it?

17:40.450 --> 17:41.951
Yeah... no.

17:41.985 --> 17:43.819
Er... no, wait. What?

17:43.854 --> 17:45.321
Take a seat, please.

17:45.355 --> 17:47.523
No, no, no, I gotta...

17:47.558 --> 17:49.192
That's a joke, right? You're kidding?

17:49.226 --> 17:52.012
I'm not known for my sense of humor.

17:52.496 --> 17:55.464
<i>[JAZZ MUSIC]</i>

17:55.499 --> 17:59.702
<i>♪ </i>

17:59.736 --> 18:01.437
Do you know my password?

18:01.471 --> 18:03.673
<i>♪ </i>

18:03.707 --> 18:05.675
The ICU is a secured area, sir.

18:05.709 --> 18:07.777
Sure it is, and you're doing
a hell of a job,

18:07.811 --> 18:09.478
but, uh, I'm late for a birthing class

18:09.513 --> 18:11.380
and this way's faster so I'm just gonna

18:11.415 --> 18:14.617
go ahead and, uh, okay. [CLEARS THROAT]

18:14.651 --> 18:17.520
That's my ICU, right? And I'm really late

18:17.554 --> 18:20.656
so I'm just gonna go ahead
and walk through it right now.

18:20.691 --> 18:22.658
So you can just

18:22.693 --> 18:24.794
step aside.

18:24.828 --> 18:28.197
Go ahead and just step...

18:28.232 --> 18:30.366
[SIGHS] Yeah.

18:30.400 --> 18:32.001
Did I mention I have cancer?

18:32.035 --> 18:38.474
<i>♪ </i>

18:41.278 --> 18:42.845
[SIGHS]

18:42.879 --> 18:46.233
<i>When you find out that you have cancer,</i>

18:46.883 --> 18:49.403
it's the worst moment.

18:49.920 --> 18:52.888
Everything is chaos and...

18:52.923 --> 18:54.690
and fear.

18:54.725 --> 18:56.692
<i>[SOMBER MUSIC]</i>

18:56.727 --> 19:00.363
When adult protection services
petitioned to have Mr. Brandt

19:00.397 --> 19:01.697
become a ward of the state,

19:01.732 --> 19:04.567
he had just got his cancer diagnosis.

19:04.601 --> 19:07.336
He was unraveling.

19:08.372 --> 19:09.872
But then Walter met Sheila.

19:09.906 --> 19:11.707
<i>[ROMANTIC MUSIC]</i>

19:11.742 --> 19:15.711
And since he's been
with Sheila, he's happy

19:15.746 --> 19:17.681
and taken care of.

19:18.448 --> 19:22.618
Will love cure Walter? No.

19:22.653 --> 19:26.355
But it will heal him in other ways.

19:27.791 --> 19:29.959
Mr. Jimenez, do you have a response?

19:29.993 --> 19:32.461
I do, Your Honor.

19:32.496 --> 19:35.798
The decision to deem Mr. Brandt
an incapacitated person

19:35.832 --> 19:37.400
was not made lightly.

19:37.434 --> 19:38.734
- Now...
- Come on.

19:38.769 --> 19:40.970
Mr. Brandt, this is for your benefit.

19:41.004 --> 19:42.938
You're petitioning
to get your rights back.

19:42.973 --> 19:45.032
Please let Mr. Jimenez finish.

19:45.066 --> 19:46.212
I'm sorry.

19:46.246 --> 19:47.943
Look, I didn't want to go there,

19:47.978 --> 19:50.746
But of the five speeding
tickets Walter got last year,

19:50.781 --> 19:52.481
one of them was near a school.

19:52.516 --> 19:55.651
His hoarding caused
a small fire in his apartment.

19:55.686 --> 19:58.387
And then Walter got aggressive
with his healthcare attendant

19:58.422 --> 20:00.289
when she tried to help him clean up.

20:00.324 --> 20:02.958
That's why the state stepped in.

20:03.316 --> 20:05.928
You believe he's a danger
to himself and to others?

20:05.962 --> 20:08.798
<i>[TENSE MUSIC]</i>

20:08.832 --> 20:09.799
<i>♪ </i>

20:09.833 --> 20:11.434
I do, Your Honor.

20:11.468 --> 20:18.474
<i>♪ </i>

20:20.000 --> 20:26.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

20:27.376 --> 20:28.794
Hey there.

20:29.453 --> 20:31.130
Can we talk for a minute?

20:34.658 --> 20:36.792
I just wanted to check in.

20:36.827 --> 20:39.428
I know we hit you with a crazy idea.

20:39.463 --> 20:41.864
We were just trying to help you
duck some red tape.

20:41.898 --> 20:44.600
Our marriage isn't red tape.

20:44.634 --> 20:46.035
I realize that.

20:46.069 --> 20:49.038
When Neil and I got married,
we made a promise

20:49.072 --> 20:53.843
to our family, to our friends, to God.

20:53.877 --> 20:56.253
It was a divine pact to each other.

20:56.288 --> 20:58.047
That's a... it's a real promise.

20:58.081 --> 20:59.782
Marriage is forever.

20:59.816 --> 21:01.984
I... I can't even imagine.

21:02.018 --> 21:03.719
Neil is our rock.

21:03.754 --> 21:06.472
- Look, Mrs. Corrigan...
- I won't abandon my family.

21:06.506 --> 21:08.023
It'd just be on paper.

21:08.058 --> 21:10.693
"Render unto Ceasar," that sort of thing.

21:10.727 --> 21:12.061
There has to be another way.

21:12.095 --> 21:13.729
We'd lose our community.

21:13.764 --> 21:15.698
We wouldn't be able
to receive the Eucharist.

21:15.732 --> 21:17.466
I understand,

21:17.501 --> 21:20.569
but is that worth more
than your son's life?

21:20.604 --> 21:23.806
<i>[SOMBER MUSIC]</i>

21:23.840 --> 21:25.658
<i>♪ </i>

21:25.692 --> 21:28.043
Hey, maybe we could get remarried.

21:28.078 --> 21:30.546
You know, when Jimmy's off
his medications.

21:30.580 --> 21:33.649
<i>♪ </i>

21:33.683 --> 21:35.484
Unfortunately, Jimmy will be on meds

21:35.519 --> 21:37.420
for the rest of his life.

21:37.454 --> 21:40.923
<i>♪ </i>

21:40.957 --> 21:42.826
This is forever?

21:43.427 --> 21:45.428
I don't see any other way around it.

21:45.462 --> 21:52.535
<i>♪ </i>

21:56.046 --> 21:57.413
Then we'll do it.

22:00.143 --> 22:07.216
<i>♪ </i>

22:10.604 --> 22:13.088
Inhale.

22:13.123 --> 22:15.925
And exhale.

22:18.628 --> 22:19.929
Okay, moms.

22:19.963 --> 22:23.158
Put all your weight on your partner.

22:24.285 --> 22:26.836
Inhale.

22:28.939 --> 22:31.106
And sway.

22:32.142 --> 22:33.776
Good.

22:33.810 --> 22:35.546
Doesn't that feel good?

22:36.672 --> 22:38.247
- You okay?
- Hm?

22:38.281 --> 22:40.816
If this is too much, we can stop.

22:40.851 --> 22:42.363
No, yeah, I'm good. I'm swaying.

22:42.397 --> 22:43.619
- Sorry.
- All right.

22:43.653 --> 22:48.309
Okay, now guide Mom down to her pillow.

22:49.626 --> 22:52.728
And moms, this is the best part.

22:52.762 --> 22:55.264
- Foot massage.
- [TITTERING]

22:55.298 --> 22:58.133
This is great if you have a headache.

22:58.168 --> 23:01.637
And who remembers
the one place not to massage?

23:01.671 --> 23:03.073
Ankles.

23:04.541 --> 23:06.775
Everyone, this is Max,
the Medical Director.

23:06.810 --> 23:08.277
Yeah, I got a follow up question.

23:08.311 --> 23:09.812
Why are we giving foot massages
when we should

23:09.846 --> 23:11.647
be discussing postpartum hemorrhaging,

23:11.681 --> 23:13.832
which is the number one cause
of maternal mortality?

23:13.867 --> 23:15.618
[UNCOMFORTABLE LAUGHTER]

23:15.652 --> 23:18.393
Not... not a joke.

23:18.395 --> 23:20.557
- Max...
- What?

23:20.624 --> 23:22.758
Rest assured that hemorrhaging

23:22.792 --> 23:24.493
is very rare, okay?

23:24.528 --> 23:26.161
Yeah, rare, but 5% of births

23:26.196 --> 23:27.914
and double that for Caesareans
and I mean,

23:27.948 --> 23:29.164
if Mom does have a headache

23:29.199 --> 23:30.666
that could be
preeclampsia or any number of...

23:30.700 --> 23:33.562
- Max, stop it.
- Sorry, sorry.

23:34.004 --> 23:37.540
Just, um... there's a lot that could...

23:38.233 --> 23:39.575
go wrong.

23:41.978 --> 23:43.102
Sorry.

23:43.136 --> 23:46.015
<i>♪ </i>

23:46.049 --> 23:48.117
So you have your settlement agreement.

23:48.151 --> 23:50.052
We'll take it to the
judge for questioning.

23:50.086 --> 23:52.855
It'll take a while before
your divorce becomes official,

23:52.889 --> 23:56.025
so when you go home we'll make
sure that we send you

23:56.059 --> 23:59.194
with enough meds to cover Jimmy
until the Medicaid kicks in.

23:59.229 --> 24:00.529
As long as Jimmy's okay.

24:00.564 --> 24:02.164
That's what's important.

24:02.198 --> 24:03.832
Where is he?

24:03.867 --> 24:06.835
<i>[TENSE MUSIC]</i>

24:06.870 --> 24:13.943
<i>♪ </i>

24:16.383 --> 24:17.762
<i>Jimmy couldn't have gone far.</i>

24:17.796 --> 24:19.782
<i>Sepsis in oncology, missing patients...</i>

24:19.783 --> 24:21.752
this isn't supposed to happen
here at New Amsterdam.

24:21.786 --> 24:23.086
Well, it's still a hospital, Max.

24:23.120 --> 24:24.220
People get sick, scared, or...

24:24.255 --> 24:26.056
- Don't say it.
- Die.

24:26.091 --> 24:27.390
Dude, I just said, "Don't say it."

24:27.424 --> 24:30.723
Why... I literally... oh, my God.

24:30.750 --> 24:32.118
- Seriously?
- Agents, have you seen

24:32.152 --> 24:33.752
a ten year old boy, straight brown hair

24:33.787 --> 24:35.855
- in the last thirty minutes?
- I have not.

24:35.889 --> 24:37.089
Hm. Right. Of course you haven't.

24:37.124 --> 24:38.858
Can I just ask, what have you seen?

24:38.892 --> 24:41.894
4 orderlies, 12 patients,
9 doctors, 17 nurses,

24:41.928 --> 24:43.429
a janitor, and 2 pregnant couples

24:43.463 --> 24:44.763
looking for building D.

24:44.798 --> 24:46.732
3 couples.

24:46.766 --> 24:49.568
Wow. Yeah, since the Pope

24:49.603 --> 24:51.637
probably isn't coming today...

24:51.671 --> 24:53.105
How about you and a few of your guys

24:53.140 --> 24:54.607
help us out in another way?

24:54.641 --> 24:58.911
<i>[FUNKY MUSIC]</i>

24:58.945 --> 25:01.046
Scent.

25:01.081 --> 25:02.648
Good dog.

25:02.682 --> 25:03.916
<i>♪ </i>

25:03.950 --> 25:06.118
[RADIO CHATTER]

25:06.153 --> 25:13.192
<i>♪ </i>

25:14.494 --> 25:15.828
Good dog.

25:15.862 --> 25:17.563
Can we go now, please?

25:18.665 --> 25:20.232
My supervisor wants you to stay put

25:20.267 --> 25:21.467
until the Pope leaves the city.

25:21.501 --> 25:22.768
Till...

25:22.802 --> 25:24.637
come on, come on!

25:24.671 --> 25:25.771
Till the Pope leaves the city?

25:25.805 --> 25:28.974
Do we... do we look like
Pope assassins to you?

25:29.009 --> 25:30.176
He doesn't even know
where his glasses are

25:30.210 --> 25:31.243
and they're on top of his head.

25:31.278 --> 25:32.244
Right? I'm a pacifist.

25:32.279 --> 25:33.612
I can't even swat a fly.

25:33.647 --> 25:35.114
We should all have

25:35.148 --> 25:36.982
a nice cup of tea.

25:37.394 --> 25:39.285
Tea? Martin and Sameera are on

25:39.319 --> 25:40.920
their way here right now.
We're gonna miss

25:40.954 --> 25:42.154
the sleepover at the Natural
History Museum

25:42.189 --> 25:43.589
and you're talking to me about tea?

25:43.623 --> 25:45.277
It's cinnamon spice.

25:46.987 --> 25:48.727
I do love cinnamon spice.

25:51.198 --> 25:52.998
- [SIGHS]
- The Museum of Natural History

25:53.033 --> 25:54.700
must be so creepy at night.

25:54.734 --> 25:56.502
Yeah, well,
you must be so creepy at night.

25:56.536 --> 25:59.271
You know, with those all dead
animals with their eyes.

25:59.306 --> 26:00.940
My Rohan never liked
to go there as a child.

26:00.974 --> 26:02.775
It's creepy.

26:02.809 --> 26:05.177
No, it's not.
It's magical, it's wonderful,

26:05.212 --> 26:07.012
and it's educational. The trifecta.

26:07.047 --> 26:08.496
You're not listening.

26:08.531 --> 26:11.317
No, you guys are having a different
conversation than I am, clearly.

26:11.351 --> 26:14.186
- Ah, Jesus!
- What's the matter?

26:14.221 --> 26:16.989
- Scalding hot.
- Uh, no, actually, it's kinda

26:17.023 --> 26:18.023
the perfect temperature.

26:18.058 --> 26:19.959
Ah, my leg's on fire.

26:19.993 --> 26:23.128
Have you been experiencing
strange sensation in your leg?

26:23.163 --> 26:25.564
<i>[TENSE MUSIC]</i>

26:25.599 --> 26:27.486
Tingling.

26:28.201 --> 26:29.802
On and off.

26:29.836 --> 26:31.742
Is it better after work hours?

26:31.776 --> 26:33.309
How did you know?

26:33.344 --> 26:35.557
You have meralgia paresthetica.

26:35.592 --> 26:38.470
- It's caused by your gun.
- My gun?

26:38.505 --> 26:40.139
Yeah, it's pressing on your lateral

26:40.173 --> 26:42.348
femoral cutaneous nerve.

26:42.382 --> 26:43.983
If you switch to a shoulder holster,

26:44.017 --> 26:46.285
your symptoms should go away.

26:47.621 --> 26:48.887
Thank you.

26:48.922 --> 26:51.223
<i>[INSPIRING MUSIC]</i>

26:51.258 --> 26:53.659
So let me ask you something.
In your line of work,

26:53.693 --> 26:55.995
do a lot of assassins stop to diagnose

26:56.029 --> 26:57.663
strangers with nerve disorders?

26:57.697 --> 27:00.699
<i>♪ </i>

27:00.734 --> 27:05.371
Dr. Sharpe, like you,
I do believe in love.

27:05.732 --> 27:07.940
But love doesn't change the law.

27:08.360 --> 27:10.876
The law grants Mr. Jimenez
the right to determine

27:10.910 --> 27:13.245
the medical decisions for Mr. Brandt

27:14.700 --> 27:17.383
Unless you have anything else to present.

27:17.744 --> 27:19.385
I don't, Your Honor.

27:20.038 --> 27:22.087
Then I'm afraid to say we're done.

27:22.374 --> 27:24.957
Legal guardianship remains
with Mr. Jimenez.

27:24.991 --> 27:26.759
Thank you, Your Honor.

27:33.010 --> 27:34.767
Walt.

27:34.801 --> 27:37.236
Let's get you home.

27:37.270 --> 27:40.239
<i>[SOMBER MUSIC]</i>

27:40.273 --> 27:47.346
<i>♪ </i>

28:14.843 --> 28:16.442
What are you doing?

28:17.944 --> 28:19.144
Hiding.

28:19.179 --> 28:21.313
Huh. If I thought I could

28:21.348 --> 28:24.049
get back up I would join you.

28:31.068 --> 28:32.925
You got a family?

28:32.959 --> 28:34.821
I'm mad at 'em.

28:36.120 --> 28:37.602
Yeah.

28:39.326 --> 28:41.100
Authority figures.

28:42.537 --> 28:44.903
I'm mad at them too.

28:46.833 --> 28:48.841
I wish I was old.

28:51.129 --> 28:52.778
I wish I was young.

28:52.812 --> 28:59.151
<i>♪ </i>

29:00.592 --> 29:02.254
Found them.

29:05.892 --> 29:10.029
Oh, honey. We were so worried about you.

29:11.441 --> 29:13.832
Are you going to live
in different houses?

29:14.254 --> 29:15.587
No.

29:15.612 --> 29:17.369
Will you still love each other?

29:17.404 --> 29:20.005
[LAUGHING] Of course.

29:21.535 --> 29:23.279
But you're gonna go to hell.

29:23.313 --> 29:27.039
<i>♪ </i>

29:27.073 --> 29:29.014
Jimmy.

29:29.751 --> 29:31.386
It... it's not that simple.

29:31.420 --> 29:34.852
Divorce is a sin. Sister Frances said so.

29:34.886 --> 29:37.156
She said sinning isn't cool.

29:37.467 --> 29:39.324
Is she wrong?

29:39.845 --> 29:42.895
No, she's right. Sinning isn't cool.

29:42.929 --> 29:45.731
So you'll go to hell
and I'll go to heaven

29:45.765 --> 29:47.499
and not be with you

29:48.084 --> 29:49.484
forever.

29:49.509 --> 29:55.207
<i>♪ </i>

29:59.078 --> 30:01.693
- Hi.
- Hi.

30:01.727 --> 30:03.916
- It's an ambush.
- I see that.

30:03.950 --> 30:08.612
So are we kicked out
of foot massage class?

30:08.637 --> 30:11.539
No but there were a lot of
people googling

30:11.573 --> 30:13.607
preeclampsia and hyperventilating.

30:13.642 --> 30:15.443
Well, hyperventilating
is kinda like Lamaze,

30:15.477 --> 30:17.578
so good practice, right?

30:18.647 --> 30:19.801
Sorry.

30:20.649 --> 30:22.450
Not funny.

30:22.484 --> 30:25.353
Kind of off my game today.

30:26.121 --> 30:29.523
- What is going on, babe?
- Ah, it's nothing.

30:31.360 --> 30:33.294
- I should get back to work.
- Max.

30:33.328 --> 30:35.796
Okay, it's just that... I mean,

30:35.831 --> 30:37.798
foot massages?

30:37.833 --> 30:40.067
And standing squats, and, uh...

30:40.102 --> 30:42.403
uh, changing doll diapers.

30:42.437 --> 30:44.105
The focus of that class is just way off.

30:44.139 --> 30:46.607
Babe, the focus of that class
is managing labor.

30:46.641 --> 30:48.976
The focus of that class is situations

30:49.011 --> 30:50.344
that you could handle with an epidural

30:50.379 --> 30:51.979
when what you need to focus on

30:52.014 --> 30:54.920
is getting ready.
I mean you... you need to get...

30:55.617 --> 30:57.088
You need to get ready.

30:58.687 --> 31:00.342
Just in case.

31:01.857 --> 31:05.055
- In case of what?
- In case I'm not there.

31:05.727 --> 31:07.432
I might not be able to

31:07.896 --> 31:10.185
carry your weight, or

31:10.665 --> 31:14.735
help you change positions,
or bring you ice chips.

31:16.872 --> 31:19.507
I might not be in there at all.
You understand?

31:19.541 --> 31:20.941
That is what you need to think about.

31:20.976 --> 31:22.610
That is what you need to get ready for.

31:22.644 --> 31:23.844
I know.

31:23.879 --> 31:25.367
And I do.

31:26.048 --> 31:27.615
Every day.

31:27.649 --> 31:30.718
<i>[SOMBER MUSIC]</i>

31:30.752 --> 31:32.386
- Yeah, but you don't...
- I don't what?

31:32.421 --> 31:33.721
I don't have public outbursts?

31:33.755 --> 31:35.689
I don't rail about maternal death rates?

31:35.724 --> 31:36.857
No, I don't.

31:36.892 --> 31:39.860
<i>♪ </i>

31:39.895 --> 31:41.554
Then how do you...

31:41.588 --> 31:45.566
<i>♪ </i>

31:45.600 --> 31:47.305
I...

31:48.070 --> 31:49.933
I look around.

31:51.440 --> 31:53.874
At everything that I have.

31:53.909 --> 31:55.849
And I focus on that.

31:55.884 --> 32:01.316
<i>♪ </i>

32:01.351 --> 32:03.613
And if it goes?

32:05.053 --> 32:07.158
Then it goes.

32:09.458 --> 32:11.162
But it's not gone yet,

32:11.927 --> 32:13.594
you hear me?

32:13.628 --> 32:16.459
- You're not gone yet.
- Mm-hmm.

32:18.100 --> 32:21.402
<i>[SENTIMENTAL MUSIC]</i>

32:21.436 --> 32:28.509
<i>♪ </i>

32:41.543 --> 32:45.344
<i>There's no improvement yet
but she is a tough cookie.</i>

32:45.379 --> 32:47.513
<i>Not that cancer cares.</i>

32:50.756 --> 32:52.454
Why was she laughing?

32:54.721 --> 32:57.190
You should hear some of their jokes.

32:59.085 --> 33:02.128
I mean, they used to name their tumors.

33:02.162 --> 33:05.231
I believe Willow's was Arnold, as in,

33:05.265 --> 33:07.467
"It's not a tum-ah."

33:07.501 --> 33:10.203
- That's pretty good.
- [LAUGHING]

33:11.973 --> 33:13.475
But it is a tumor.

33:15.309 --> 33:17.643
Grace comes in many forms.

33:17.678 --> 33:19.105
Hm.

33:23.984 --> 33:25.485
You would have been proud of me today.

33:25.519 --> 33:27.553
- Yeah?
- Yeah, I pulled a Max.

33:27.588 --> 33:29.822
How? Had multiple panic
attacks in the hospital,

33:29.857 --> 33:32.425
frightened pregnant women,
encouraged sin?

33:32.459 --> 33:34.427
- No.
- Mm.

33:34.461 --> 33:36.295
No, I, um...

33:36.330 --> 33:37.830
I got way more involved

33:37.865 --> 33:39.834
with a patient than I should have.

33:40.367 --> 33:42.087
Feels good, doesn't it?

33:43.884 --> 33:45.518
Not when it doesn't work out.

33:46.373 --> 33:47.740
Yeah.

33:49.543 --> 33:50.943
[KNOCKING]

33:52.646 --> 33:55.281
Um, sorry to interrupt.

33:55.315 --> 33:57.617
Dr. Sharpe, can we talk about
Walter's next steps?

33:57.651 --> 33:58.895
Yeah.

34:05.225 --> 34:07.360
The first thing we have to do
is get Walter back to Mt. Zion.

34:07.394 --> 34:09.629
- Uh, Baptist.
- What?

34:09.663 --> 34:12.331
No, no. He's at, um...

34:13.900 --> 34:15.967
Oh. Baptist.

34:16.003 --> 34:18.571
Yeah, you're right. Sorry.

34:19.639 --> 34:21.274
How many are you taking care of?

34:21.308 --> 34:24.377
Wards of the state? Um, ten?

34:24.411 --> 34:25.777
Seems rather a lot.

34:25.812 --> 34:28.714
Well, it is, but I wish
I could take on more.

34:28.748 --> 34:30.882
There are so many seniors
out there alone.

34:30.918 --> 34:33.553
No husband or wife, no children.

34:33.587 --> 34:35.487
And the ones like Walter, they require

34:35.522 --> 34:36.789
even more time and attention.

34:36.822 --> 34:38.858
Even more care.

34:40.920 --> 34:43.121
You mean like that?

34:44.398 --> 34:47.366
<i>[SENTIMENTAL MUSIC]</i>

34:47.400 --> 34:48.967
<i>♪ </i>

34:49.002 --> 34:51.670
Yeah, like that.

34:51.705 --> 34:55.574
<i>♪ </i>

34:55.609 --> 34:57.009
I have an idea.

34:57.043 --> 35:00.012
<i>♪ </i>

35:00.047 --> 35:02.248
<i>Well, this is one for the books.</i>

35:02.282 --> 35:04.684
You want me to terminate
his guardianship?

35:04.718 --> 35:06.419
Yes, Your Honor.

35:06.453 --> 35:08.688
The ruling that I just
confirmed in your favor?

35:08.722 --> 35:10.590
Yes, Your Honor.

35:10.624 --> 35:12.391
Can I ask why?

35:12.426 --> 35:14.994
Actually, it was Dr. Sharpe's idea.

35:15.028 --> 35:16.896
But there is one condition.

35:16.930 --> 35:18.397
One condition?

35:18.432 --> 35:20.766
If Mr. Jimenez is not going to be

35:20.801 --> 35:22.729
Mr. Brandt's guardian, who will?

35:23.370 --> 35:24.939
His wife.

35:25.539 --> 35:27.907
I didn't realize
you were married, Mr. Brandt.

35:29.376 --> 35:30.843
That's the one condition.

35:30.877 --> 35:34.380
All I want is for someone
to look out for Walter.

35:34.414 --> 35:36.415
Someone with his best interests at heart.

35:36.450 --> 35:38.036
And I accept.

35:38.819 --> 35:40.519
Me too.

35:40.554 --> 35:46.792
<i>♪ </i>

35:46.827 --> 35:48.961
Dr. Goodwin, grazie.

35:48.996 --> 35:51.397
I apologize for any inconvenience.

35:51.431 --> 35:53.065
Oh, it's no inconvenience at all.

35:53.100 --> 35:55.568
Actually, that's not true.
It was a lot of inconvenience.

35:55.602 --> 35:56.969
[LAUGHS]

35:57.004 --> 36:00.039
If there is any way I can
express my gratitude,

36:00.073 --> 36:01.474
just let me know.

36:01.508 --> 36:02.477
Mm.

36:03.410 --> 36:04.543
Actually...

36:04.578 --> 36:06.045
Hm?

36:06.079 --> 36:07.982
There is.

36:09.349 --> 36:12.445
- Dr. Reynolds?
- Oh, just in time.

36:13.020 --> 36:15.821
Hey, guys. Uh, Jimmy,
I'd like you to meet someone.

36:15.856 --> 36:19.925
This is Cardinal Mancini,
the Pope's right hand man.

36:19.960 --> 36:21.494
The Pope?

36:21.528 --> 36:22.828
Mm-hmm.

36:22.863 --> 36:24.730
It's a great honor, Cardinal, sir.

36:24.765 --> 36:26.668
We're big fans.

36:27.434 --> 36:31.130
I talked to His Holiness
about your predicament.

36:32.839 --> 36:35.350
The Pope says it's cool.

36:35.384 --> 36:38.511
<i>[EMOTIONAL MUSIC]</i>

36:38.545 --> 36:43.649
<i>♪ </i>

36:43.684 --> 36:44.984
You guys will not believe

36:45.018 --> 36:46.686
- what I just went through.
- Iggy.

36:46.720 --> 36:47.987
All right, so if we're gonna
make the flashlight tour

36:48.021 --> 36:49.488
of the museum we gotta get going.

36:49.523 --> 36:50.790
- Put that away.
- Ooh, hang on a second.

36:50.824 --> 36:52.091
What? What is it?

36:52.125 --> 36:53.634
She doesn't want to go.

36:53.669 --> 36:54.728
What are you talking about?

36:54.762 --> 36:55.828
Of course she wants to go. That's what

36:55.862 --> 36:57.129
we talked about. We're going, right?

36:57.164 --> 36:58.764
- Put that stuff away.
- Iggy, Iggy.

36:58.799 --> 37:01.734
Stop talking and listen.

37:02.903 --> 37:04.036
Okay.

37:04.071 --> 37:06.124
Wanna tell him what you told me?

37:09.176 --> 37:11.010
Okay, come on. Come on, bug.

37:11.044 --> 37:13.272
You gotta tell me what's going on.
What's wrong?

37:13.747 --> 37:15.648
The museum is scary.

37:15.682 --> 37:18.050
The museum is not scary, it's a museum.

37:18.085 --> 37:20.119
And you told me
that you wanted to go, right?

37:20.153 --> 37:22.688
'Cause you wanted to go.

37:24.691 --> 37:26.311
I... I just, uh...

37:27.427 --> 37:28.771
I...

37:30.230 --> 37:32.732
You know, I just...
I wanna share all the things

37:32.766 --> 37:35.067
that I loved the most with you
because that's my favorite part

37:35.102 --> 37:36.446
about being your dad.

37:37.237 --> 37:42.541
But maybe sometimes I'm not
the... the best listener.

37:42.576 --> 37:45.644
Even though that is technically my job.

37:47.447 --> 37:50.483
Maybe sometimes at home you
don't get the best of me.

37:52.018 --> 37:55.421
I'm sorry. I always want you
to have the best of me.

37:55.455 --> 37:58.724
<i>[BITTERSWEET MUSIC]</i>

37:58.759 --> 38:00.726
Okay?

38:00.761 --> 38:02.595
What do you think? Hug?

38:02.629 --> 38:04.897
You're in? Come here. Meet me half way.

38:04.931 --> 38:07.099
Get up here. Oh, my gosh you get so big.

38:07.134 --> 38:09.034
- Can I get in on that?
- Of course.

38:09.069 --> 38:10.669
Mmm.

38:10.704 --> 38:15.708
<i>♪ </i>

38:15.742 --> 38:18.611
[LAUGHTER]

38:18.645 --> 38:21.247
Does anyone else wanna speak?

38:25.536 --> 38:26.786
All right, then.

38:27.246 --> 38:29.040
I'll see you guys tomorrow morning.

38:29.589 --> 38:31.125
I messed up.

38:32.926 --> 38:34.462
Uh...

38:36.963 --> 38:40.635
I was in trouble and...

38:41.835 --> 38:43.638
instead of asking for help...

38:44.738 --> 38:48.007
I just pushed everyone away.

38:49.509 --> 38:51.771
I didn't think I had any friends left.

38:52.579 --> 38:53.981
I thought, well,

38:54.681 --> 38:57.183
I ruin all my relationships.

38:59.019 --> 39:02.073
And I was wondering...

39:03.190 --> 39:06.759
Why even bother recovering, you know?

39:08.195 --> 39:11.730
Why not let myself sink deeper
down the hole?

39:13.033 --> 39:15.378
Didn't think I had anything left.

39:15.802 --> 39:17.797
I have nothing to go back to.

39:20.258 --> 39:21.801
But then, um...

39:23.109 --> 39:25.054
the other night, uh...

39:26.646 --> 39:29.559
a friend of mine came to visit and...

39:32.353 --> 39:34.820
I'm just really grateful that he did.

39:38.825 --> 39:40.526
Thank you.

39:40.560 --> 39:42.194
<i>[NEKO CASE'S
"I WISH I WAS THE MOON" PLAYS]</i>

39:42.229 --> 39:46.165
<i>♪ I wish I was the moon tonight ♪</i>

39:46.199 --> 39:48.534
Out of the night that covers me,

39:48.568 --> 39:50.936
black as the pit from pole to pole

39:50.971 --> 39:55.641
I thank whatever gods may be
for my unconquerable soul.

39:55.675 --> 39:59.345
<i>♪ God bless me I'm a free man ♪</i>

39:59.379 --> 40:03.649
<i>♪ With no place free to go</i>

40:03.683 --> 40:07.219
<i>♪ Paralyzed and collared-tight ♪</i>

40:07.254 --> 40:11.657
<i>♪ No pills for what I fear</i>

40:11.691 --> 40:14.886
<i>♪ This is crazy</i>

40:14.921 --> 40:21.527
<i>♪ I wish I was the moon tot ♪</i>

40:21.561 --> 40:25.986
<i>♪ Chimney falls as lovers blaze ♪</i>

40:26.021 --> 40:29.241
<i>♪ Thought that I was young</i>

40:29.275 --> 40:31.977
<i>♪ Now I've freezing hands
and bloodless veins ♪</i>

40:32.012 --> 40:34.079
[YELPS] No!

40:34.114 --> 40:35.848
What have you done with my daughter?

40:35.882 --> 40:40.494
<i>♪ Numb as I've become, I'm so tired ♪</i>

40:40.528 --> 40:44.375
<i>♪ And I wish I was the moon</i>

40:44.409 --> 40:46.575
<i>♪ I'm so tired</i>

40:46.609 --> 40:48.768
<i>♪ I'm so tired</i>

40:48.803 --> 40:53.490
<i>♪ And I wish I was the moon</i>

40:53.524 --> 40:56.902
<i>♪ Tonight</i>

41:07.247 --> 41:09.214
Jeez. Feels like I walked into

41:09.249 --> 41:11.050
the final scene of "Miss Saigon."

41:12.953 --> 41:14.286
We were worried about you, hon.

41:14.321 --> 41:16.207
Yeah, you scared us.

41:16.756 --> 41:19.858
Yeah, we, um... for a minute there

41:19.893 --> 41:22.755
we thought you were "Croaklahoma."

41:27.000 --> 41:28.934
Oh, my...

41:28.969 --> 41:31.971
[LAUGHING]

41:32.005 --> 41:35.441
Oh, that's twisted, man. I love it.

41:35.475 --> 41:38.978
You know, you also could have
gone with "Oaklymphoma."

41:39.012 --> 41:40.713
See that's good. That's better.

41:40.747 --> 41:43.215
- Or "A Little Night Mucus."
- [LAUGHTER]

41:44.351 --> 41:47.052
"Fiddler on the Puke"? Does that work?

41:47.087 --> 41:48.287
- Ew.
- It's good.

41:48.321 --> 41:49.922
Why is it ew? Why is that ew?

41:49.956 --> 41:52.091
"Catch me if you Cancer."

41:52.125 --> 41:54.393
"The King and Eye Cancer."

41:54.427 --> 41:55.794
Very specific.

41:55.829 --> 41:57.062
[LAUGHTER]

41:57.097 --> 41:59.832
Good one, Mike. An actual musical.

41:59.866 --> 42:02.267
So "Anything Ghosts"
is a pretty good one.

42:02.302 --> 42:03.671
"Anything Ghosts!"

42:05.205 --> 42:07.172
Uh, "Gurney Boys."

42:07.207 --> 42:08.741
[LAUGHTER]

42:08.775 --> 42:11.010
It's a good one. That's a good one.

42:11.044 --> 42:13.012
[LAUGHTER]

42:13.046 --> 42:14.807
How about this?

